    object_speaker:        'A thing, material, or non-human presence takes on speech or implied interiority.',
    public_voice:          'The poem carries a social voice larger than one speaker: crowd, broadcast, slogan, or institution.',
    domestic_voice:        'Speech begins from the house, room, family, or ordinary interior life.',
    threshold_speaker:     'The speaker stands at a crossing point: leaving, entering, looking through, or refusing passage.',
    memory_fragment:       'A partial, non-linear recollection — the poem captures a piece of the past as it surfaces, incomplete.',
    scene:                 'A present-tense moment rendered in space — the poem unfolds as a place you can stand inside.',
    witness:               'The poem enacts the act of seeing and recording, as if giving testimony.',
    monologue:             'Extended address by a single voice, uninterrupted and self-contained.',
    confession:            'The disclosure of something difficult or hidden — the poem as an act of speaking what has been held.',
    lament:                'Sustained mourning — the poem dwells inside grief without seeking resolution.',
    invocation:            'The poem calls something forth: a person, a quality, a memory, a presence.',
    prayer:                'Appeal or devotion directed beyond the self, toward the uncertain or the unreachable.',
    chant:                 'A repetitive incantatory structure — meaning accumulates through rhythm and recurrence.',
    manifesto:             'Declarative and positional — the poem asserts a way of seeing as if staking ground.',
    warning:               'The poem speaks in a cautionary or prophetic register, addressed to the future.',
    farewell:              'Leave-taking — the poem as a form of ending or final departure.',
    meditation:            'Reflective pressure held over time, where the poem thinks by circling its subject.',
    catalogue:             'Accumulation through listing — the poem builds force by gathering objects, scenes, or sensations.',
    blessing:              'A wish or protection extended outward, even when its faith is uncertain.',
    dream_record:          'A scene held in dream logic: vivid, displaced, or resistant to ordinary causality.',
    parable:               'A small story or image carrying an ethical, spiritual, or social pressure beyond itself.',
    letter:                'Address shaped as correspondence, whether or not it expects a reply.',
    threshold_crossing:    'The poem stages passage from one state, world, room, or self toward another.',
    refusal:               'The poem resists an imposed logic, command, role, or interpretation.',
    shadow:                'The trace or absence that follows without being named — what a presence leaves behind.',
    child:                 'Youth, vulnerability, the past self as a living presence in the poem.',
    room:                  'Interior space as containment — the poem happens inside enclosure, bounded.',
    house:                 'Domestic structure as inheritance — what we are sheltered and burdened by.',
    window:                'A threshold for looking — the poem frames what can and cannot be crossed.',
    glass:                 'Transparency, fragility, reflection — the permeable border between inner and outer.',
    light:                 'Illumination as presence, arrival, or revelation — what makes visible.',
    eye:                   'The organ of witness — perception, judgment, the experience of being seen.',
    voice:                 'Speech without visible body — presence sustained through sound alone.',
    flowers:               'Beauty, transience, offering — what blooms briefly and cannot be held.',
    faith:                 'Belief, trust, devotion — the poem in relation to what cannot be verified.',
    sky:                   'Expanse, distance, what cannot be held or entered — openness as subject.',
    water:                 'Flow, cleansing, drowning, or passage — a force that carries feeling elsewhere.',
    mirror:                'Reflection and doubling — the self seen as altered, split, or returned.',
    street:                'Public movement and exposure, where private feeling enters social space.',
    forest:                'A living threshold: danger, childhood fear, or unmanaged memory.',
    bed:                   'Rest, illness, vulnerability, or the place where perception becomes unstable.',
    fire:                  'Warmth, destruction, ritual, or a small center of survival.',
    table:                 'The social surface of eating, family, exchange, and observation.',
    tree:                  'Rooted witness, seasonal time, or a figure that holds memory in place.',
    animal:                'Non-human life as witness, companion, appetite, or omen.',
    food:                  'Taste, hunger, care, commerce, and the body\'s memory of the world.',
    cloth:                 'Covering, costume, protection, wrapping, or the surface of social presentation.',
    paper:                 'Record, message, advertisement, archive, or fragile proof.',
    screen:                'Mediated vision: image, broadcast, noise, or technological distance.',
    door:                  'Entry, refusal, boundary, or the possibility of leaving.',
    sea:                   'Large departure, dissolution, origin, or the horizon of return.',
